occurrences.line_text: But when he lookt about on euery syde,
At length he heard vnder the forrests syde
With a wyld man soft footing by his syde,
He started vp, and snatching neare his syde
And all the way he went, on euery syde
But his blind eye, that syded Paridell,
Ambitious Sylla, and sterne Marius,
Whiles old Syluanus slept in shady arber sownd.
So towards old Syluanus they her bring;
And old Syluanus selfe bethinkes not, what
To do their seruice to Syluanus old,
In all his speach, was Syluius his sonne,
That as a sacred Symbole it may dwell
And shrunken synewes of her chosen knight,
And rend his flesh, and his owne synewes eat.
And said, Why Archimago, lucklesse syre,
And wield the world, she claymed for her syre,
And said, Ah wretched sonne of wofull syre,
Who all in rage his Sea-god syre besought,
Which hearing his rash Syre, began to rend
That name of natiue syre did fowle vpbrayd,
He was an aged syre, all hory gray,
Great thankes and goodly meed to that good syre,
Then turning to his Palmer said, Old syre
Said he then to the Palmer, Reuerend syre,
Nor that sage Pylian syre, which did suruiue
Their aged Syre, thus eased of his crowne,
As for her Syre and king her seemed best;
Therefore old Syre thy course do thereunto apply.
Of mortall Syre, or other liuing wight,
Her Sea-god syre she dearely did perswade,
Yet was that other swayne this elders syre,
And she her selfe her syre, of whom she was yborne.
She syre and mother is her selfe alone,
First was a sage old Syre, that had to name
From that sad land, where he his syre did quell,
Then came to them a good old aged syre,
There he was welcom'd of that honest syre,
He thus replyde; Now surely syre, I find,
Which she streight way for dread least, if her syre
And Bellamour in bands, till that her syre
Did weene, vnwares, that her vnlucky lo t
T rue is, that whilome that good Poet sayd,
Threatning to chastize me, as doth t'a chyld pertaine.
It were t'abandon noble cheuisaunce,
T'abate all spasme, and soke the swelling bruze,
He now t'abhorre and loath her person had procured.
In faithfull loue, t'abide for euer more,
Vnto the crooke t'abide the balefull stowre,
And greater shame t'abide so great misprize,
He bad him stand, t'abide the bitter stoure
He shew'd him painted in a table plaine,
Like a broad table did it selfe dispred,
A table for eternall moniment
He on the table dasht, as ouerthrowne,
And the fayre mayd the table ta'ne away,
Wherein were many tables faire dispred,
Tho were the tables taken all away,
T'abridg their iourney long, and lingring day;
More hard for hungry steed t'abstaine from pleasant lare.
To threat to him, that minds his chaunce t'abye?
So praying him t'accept her seruice euermore.
But each the other vow'd t'accompany,
That seem'd full hard t'accord two things so far in dout.
Till she repaired haue her tackles spent,
T'adore thing so diuine as beauty, were but right.
T'adorne thy forme according thy desart,
That goodly seem'd t'adorne her royall state,
Shall be t'aduance thy goodly chastitee,
Each labouring t'aduance the others gest,
Which doen he gan aloft t'aduance his arme,
Whereof she now bethinking, gan t'aduize,
He stayed not t'aduize, which way were best
T'aduize him better, then by such a traine
For death t'adward I ween'd did appertaine
He on himselfe had ta'en, and rayling rymes had sprad.
Your stubborne hart t'affect with fraile infirmity.
T'afflict the creatures, which therein did dwell,
T'afflict the other Saxons vnsubdewd;
The more t'aggrate his God with such his blouddy guize.
Were with a snake, whose head & tail were fast co[m]byned.
Her huge long taile her den all ouerspred,
And rushed forth, hurling her hideous taile
And turning fierce, her speckled taile aduaunst,
An hatefull Snake, the which his taile vptyes
Did him appease; then downe his taile he hong
A foxes taile, with dong all fowly dight;
Of his huge taile he quite a sunder cleft,
And passed fairely forth. He turning taile,
Vnto his Tygres taile, and shot at him apace.
Ouer his horses taile aboue a stryde:
That with her wreathed taile her middle did enfold.
And her long taile and fethers strongly shooke,
A Dragons taile, whose sting without redresse
Tho with her huge long taile she at him strooke,
So was he stound with stroke of her huge taile.
With his long taile the bryzes brush away.
And full of Argus eyes their tailes dispredden wide.
And by the tailes together firmely bound,
And her perfections with his error taint:
That which of them to take, in diuerse doubt they been.
That path they take, that beaten seemd most bare,
Then with the Sunne take Sir, your timely rest,
Therefore with me ye may take vp your In
And dreames, gan now to take more sound repast,
And in her many troubles did most pleasure take.
For by his mightie science he could take
Whose forged beauty he did take in hand,
Life from Sansfoy thou tookst, Sansloy shall fro[m] thee take.
To take the solace of the open aire,
A seely Lambe farre from the flocke does take,
Here take thy louers token on thy pate.
And his vnready weapons gan in hand to take.
And me thy worthy meed vnto thy Leman take.
Who her as willingly to grace did take,
He forst to castle strong to take their flight,
But be of cheare, and comfort to you take:
Henceforth sir knight, take to you wonted strength,
But when as none of them he saw him take,
All keepe the broad high way, and take delight
And taught him how to take assured hold
What end (quoth she) should cause vs take such paine,
So leaue they take of Coelia, and her daughters three.
High heauen behold the tedious toyle, ye for me take.
That from thenceforth he shund the like to take,
Yet sparckling fire, and bad thereof take heed;
So courteous conge both did giue and take,
The doome of iust reuenge, and take delight
And take away this long lent loathed light:
Take not away now got, which none would giue to me.
From off the earth to take his aerie flight.
O Goddesse, (for such I thee take to bee)
But he that last left helpe away did take,
Henceforth take heede of that thou now hast past,
Disburdned her. Their way they forward take
Behold, Ã´ man, that toilesome paines doest take
That of no wordly thing he care did take;
Take what thou please of all this surplusage;
Would tempt his guest, to take thereof assay:
Ne man nor beast may rest, or take repast,
How to take life from that dead-liuing swaine,
One of Malegers cursed darts did take,
To take him from his steed full tenderly,
And of our safetie good heede to take;
And chaungd her weary side, the better ease to take.
What meanes shall she out seeke, or what wayes take?
And his last fate him from thee take away,
Shall take the crowne, that was his fathers right,
That of the time doth dew aduauntage take;
Vnto thy selfe, and equall courage to thee take.
That mortall speare she in her hand did take,
Ne doest by others death ensample take,
Least afterwards it be too late to take thy flight.
Where, doubtfull which to take, her to reskew,
To take that way, in which that Damozell
To whom the Prince; Dwarfe, comfort to thee take,
And doth not highest God vouchsafe to take
But from her louing side the tender babes to take.
But when he stayd, to flight againe she did her take.
May meet againe, and each take happie chance.
But none of those excuses could take place;
To take to his new loue, and leaue her old despysd.
What Ladie, man? (said Trompart) take good hart,
I take no keepe of her (said Paridell)
And of faire Britomart ensample take,
Therefore, faire Sir, do comfort to you take,
And often to him calling, to take surer hould.
And take me for their Ioue, whiles Ioue to earth is gone.
Tho blinding him againe, his way he forth did take.
Henceforth faire Lady comfort to you take,
Take then to you this Dame of mine (quoth hee)
Amongst those famous ympes of Greece, did take
Wouldst gather faine, and yet no paines wouldst take:
That seeke perforce her from you both to take,
That dare fro me thinke Florimell to take.
And of them all the victour should his sister take.
Lo faitour there thy meede vnto thee take,
Now stood, came forth in hast to take his part,
Now hurtling round aduantage for to take:
In hope to take him prisoner, where he stood on ground.
And lightly issewd forth to take his lot.
A paire of redwhot yron tongs did take
Did comfort take, or in his troubled sight
But comfort take: for by this heauens light
To be his loue, and take him for her Lord,
And vnto her his congee came to take.
Full oftentimes she leaue of him did take;
Then did he take that chaced Squire, and layd
There gan they change their sides, and new parts take;
For Paridell did take to Druons side,
Dislikefull paine, so sad a taske to take,
To take on him that paine: whose great desire
Faire lawnds, to take the sunne in season dew;
When to Ioues pallace she doth take her way;
That of his wylinesse his name doth take,
Ne dayly food did take, ne nightly sleepe,
That learned Ptolomaee his hight did take,
And each of either take his share aright.
Take here your owne, that doth you best beseeme,
Then doth he take the spoile of them at will,
Who all that comes doth take, and therewith fill
In vaine therefore doest thou now take in hand,
For take thy ballaunce, if thou be so wise,
Now take the right likewise, sayd Artegale,
Whereof to make due tryall, one did take
Lo there Sir Guyon, take to you the steed,
Who so vpon him selfe will take the skill
Could take no rest, ne would receiue reliefe,
Goe streight, and take with thee, to witnesse it,
Vnto the wall his way did fearelesse take,
That will not take the offer of good hope,
But her besought to take it well in gree,
She stayd not to aduise which way to take;
Then shalt thou take him to thy loued fere,
He vp did take, and with him brought away,
Of which he in faire weather wont to take great store.
That they the whiles may take lesse heedie keepe,
To leaue his proper forme, and other shape to take.
She gan take hart, and looke vp ioyfully:
And she take comfort, which God now did send:
He did him selfe encourage, and take better cheare.
To be my loue, and take me for her Lord,
And in anothers losse great pleasure take,
And take great ioy to publish it to many,
Then from her mouth the gobbet she does take,
Yet he past on, and seem'd of them to take no keepe.
And for this Mayd, whose party thou doest take,
To take defiaunce at a Ladies word
To take Briana for his louing fere,
To take me vp (as this young man did see)
Would to no bed, nor take no kindely sleepe,
To take him vp behinde vpon his steed:
And blot of all that armes vppon them take,
To take the ayre, and heare the thrushes song,
Which way to take: now West he went a while,
But gan himselfe addresse to take her part.
Thinking to take them from that hylding hound:
The which full gladly they did take in glee,
But faire Serene all night could take no rest,
The whiles the saluage man did take his steede,
And to him leaping, vengeance thought to take
He from you take that chiefedome, which ye doe abuse.
Ensample take of Mirabellaes case,
Great perill of his life, and restlesse paines did take.
Then gan they to deuize what course to take:
Thereof by force to take their beastly pleasure.
The rest take if they would, he her to him would hold.
Ne stayeth leaue to take, before his friends doe dye.
To whom they both agreed to take their way,
Now all vnwares, and take the spoyle away;
And thence did all the spoyles and threasures take,
The litle babe, to take thereof a sight.
From mothers pap I taken was vnfit:
But Trompart stoutly stayd to taken heed,
That none thereof could euer taken hold,
To taken counsell of their common cares;
Tho were the tables taken all away,
I taken was from nourses tender pap,
Was taken with her loue, and by her closely lay.
Of two grim lyons, taken from the wood,
They haue him taken captiue, though it grieue him sore.
Tho when they had long time there taken rest,
That ere she backe could turne to taken heed,
Then was I taken and before her brought:
I hauing armes then taken, gan auise
And now perforce they haue him prisoner taken;
Which long agoe he taken had in hond:
Had hid themselues, or taken further flight:
(Said she) that taken haue this toylesome paine
Taken in hand th'exploit, being theretoo
He rather should haue taken vp behind.
With them also was taken Coridon,
In drowsie fit he findes: of nothing he takes keepe.
And in his falsed fancy he her takes
So marcheth home, and by her takes the knight,
Sometimes Diana he her takes to bee,
To weete what course he takes, and how he fares;
Your court'sie takes on you anothers due offence.
Attonce he wards and strikes, he takes and payes,
He liues, but takes small ioy of his renowne;
Possesseth him, and of his sweetnesse takes her fill.
The rest he leaues in ground: so takes in hond
Who being freed, from one a weapon fiercely takes.
Poeana takes to wife:
And so well skild; nathlesse he takes great ioy
As rated Spaniell takes his burden vp for feare.
He giues to this, from that he takes away.
Prince Arthur takes the enterprize
Why takest not of that same fruit of gold,
Whom to thy selfe thou takest quite away?
Yet no man for them taketh paines or care,
Taketh his nimble wings, and soone away is gone.
How then? of all loue taketh equall vew:
That taketh vengeaunce of his peoples spoile.
And taking by the hand that Faeries sonne,
Taking aduantage of his open iaw,
Then taking Congï¿½ fÂ© of that virgin pure,
And taking armes, the Britons to her drew;
So taking courteous conge he behight,
Aboue three furlongs, taking his full course,
Who taking it out of her tender hond,
Then taking thrise three haires from off her head,
Downe taking, her therein appareled,
Tho vp him taking in their tender hands,
Which done, she passed forth not taking leaue,
Whose scoffed words he taking halfe in scorne,
And wise Cambina taking by her side
But taking with her louely Amoret,
With Beares and Tygers taking heauie part,
And taking leaue of all, with him did beare
And each one taking part in others aide,
And taking downe the shield, with me did it retaine.
And many riuers taking vnder hand
And taking vsurie of time forepast,
Who taking her from me, his owne loue left astray.
Yet taking leaue of her, he did depart.
Then taking leaue of them, she forward went,
And taking with him, as his vanquisht thrall,
Taking them vp vnto her stately throne,
Taking aduantage, and her yet fresh woes,
Then taking humble leaue of that great Queene,
Of whom yet taking leaue, thenceforth he went
And taking from her hand a ring of gould,
Neither of other taking pitty nor remorse.
Whereof he taking oddes, streight bids him dight
So taking counsell of a wise man red,
So taking courteous leaue, they parted twayne,
Of which occasion Aldine taking hold,
Then taking vp that Recreants shield and speare,
For want of taking heede vnto the same,
So taking them apart into his cell,
And from him taking his owne whip, therewith
So humbly taking leaue, she turnd aside,
And taking vp brought home, and noursed well
So taking leaue of that same gentle swaine,
So taking leaue of his faire Pastorell,
Ne wist yet, how his talants to vnfold;
Did come too neare, and with his talants play,
How can I tell, but that his talants may
With griping talaunts armd to greedy fight,
The wofull tale that Treuisan had told,
To tell this ruefull tale; thy sight could win thee grace.
Tell on, faire Sir, said she, that dolefull tale,
When of his pitteous tale he end did make;
Yet should it be a pleasant tale, to tell
So ended he his tale, where I this Canto end.
And sent them home to tell a piteous tale,
So smooth of tongue, and subtile in his tale.
The Infant hearkned wisely to her tale,
This wofull tale? or how those Brigants vyle,
And greatly ioyed merry tales to faine,
And all that fained is, as leasings, tales, and lies.
And faynes to weaue false tales and leasings bad,
And forst t'alight, on foot mote algates fare,
T'alight, and rest their wearie limbs awhile.
Your eies, your eares, your tongue, your talk restraine
He staid not lenger talke, but with fierce ire
Prouoking him by her outrageous talke,
But to occasion him to further talke,
For little lust had she to talke of ought,
Shun secresie, and talke in open sight:
They fall to strokes, the frute of too much talke:
Whiles thus she talked, and whiles thus she toyd,
From Faery court. So talked they, the whiles
Thus as they talked, loe where nigh at hand
Ne euer ought but of their true loues talkt,
And talk't of pleasant things, the night away to weare.
Whylest thus he talkt, the knight with greedy eare
The sayling Pine, the Cedar proud and tall,
Vnto his foe, a Gyant huge and tall,
Of tall young men, all hable armes to sownd,
From his tall steed, he rusht into the thicke,
As a tall ship tossed in troublous seas,
His portaunce terrible, and stature tall,
Tall yeomen seemed they, and of great might,
There placed was a caudron wide and tall,
And the tall trees with leaues apparelled,
A comely personage of stature tall,
I weene, would you misseeme; for ye bene tall,
And in his hand a tall young oake he bore,
From lowest Iuniper to Ceder tall,
Nathlesse thereto he was full stout and tall,
A tall young man from thence not farre away,
Yet seuenteene yeares, but tall and faire of face
That made them grow so high t'all honorable hap.
And standing on his tiptoes, to seeme tall,
She bath'd her brest, the boyling heat t'allay;
The hight of three the tallest sonnes of mortall seed.
T'allure weake trauellers, whom gotten they did kill.
And offered faire gifts t'allure her sight,
That with his talnesse seemd to threat the skye,
His name was Talus, made of yron mould,
Vntill that Talus had his pride represt,
Ne wight with him but onely Talus went.
And bad his seruant Talus to inuent
But Talus, that could like a limehound winde her,
Of Iustice, which in Talus hand did lye;
All which when Talus throughly had perfourmed,
Whom when so lewdly minded Talus found,
Therefore he Talus to them sent, t'inquire
When Talus saw they all the field forsooke
But Talus by the backe the boaster hent,
His mighty hand to shend, he Talus sent
Him Talus tooke out of perplexitie,
But Talus vsde in times of ieopardy
Then Talus forth issuing from the tent,
But when they thought on Talus hands to lay,
Talus brings newes to Britomart
In womans bondage, Talus to her brought;
That it was Talus, Artegall his groome;
Till she againe thus sayd; Talus be bold,
She vnto Talus forth return'd againe,
And mounting to her steede, bad Talus guide her on.
To seeke her Knight, as Talus her did guide:
Ne lesse did Talus suffer sleepe to seaze
Whom soone as Talus spide by glims of night,
Yet Talus after them apace did plie,
Talus desir'd, that he might haue prepared
But Talus mote not be admitted to her part.
Whiles Talus watched at the dore all night.
But that swift Talus did the formost win;
Ne wight but onely Talus with him went,
And by his stirrup Talus did attend,
whom Talus doth dismay,
But Talus soone him ouertooke, and backward drew.
With onely Talus wayting diligent,
But chiefly Talus with his yron flayle,
Talus into the sea did forth issew,
But Talus sternely did vpon them set,
And Talus to reuoke from the right way,
But Talus hearing her so lewdly raile,
There was the speedy Tamar, which deuides
T'ambitious Rome, and did their rule obay,
He that the stubborne Sprites can wisely tame,
To tame, and ryde their backes not made to beare;
And sturdie courage tame with dreadfull aw,
And with streight diet tame his stubborne malady.
With her, who so will raging Furor tame,
With liquid waues, fiers Vulcans rage to tame,
And Orcus tame, whom nothing can perswade,
And them with maystring discipline doth tame,
The powre to rule the billowes, and the waues to tame.
That no one beast in forrest wylde or tame,
With many kindes of medicines meete, to tame
Threatning to yoke them tow & tame their corage stout.
Of doughty Calidore, supprest and tamed,
She wist not how t'amend, nor how it to withstond.
T'amend what was amisse, and put in right aray.
Dame Venus sonne that tameth stubborne youth
Of Faerie knights and fairest Tanaquill,
He dying left the fairest Tanaquill,
And long time hauing tand his tawney hide
And face all tand with scorching sunny ray,
His face with smoke was tand, and eyes were bleard,
Which thou vpon thy selfe hast lately ta'ne?
That hast a thanklesse seruice on thee ta'ne,
And the fayre mayd the table ta'ne away,
As still are wont t'annoy the walled towne,
There thirstie Tantalus hong by the chin;
Lo Tantalus, I here tormented lye:
Nay, nay, thou greedie Tantalus (quoth he)
And in those Tapets weren fashioned
And gan to doubt, least she him sought t'appeach
And thought t'appeale from that, which was decreed,
Made her to change her hew, and hidden loue t'appeare.
So easie is, t'appease the stormie wind
Haue secret powre, t'appease inflamed rage:
That did not seeke t'appease their deadly hate,
His steed eke seem'd t'apply his steps to his intent.
For thy, she thither cast her course t'apply,
Still when he sought t'approch vnto him ny,
T'approue the vnknowen purpose of eternall fate.
And with blasphemous bannes high God in peeces tare.
And open gash therein: were not his targe,
Then gan he thinke, perforce with sword and targe
Quartred athwart, and bearing in his targe
His target alwayes ouer her pretended;
Proud Tarquin, and too lordly Lentulus,
With many towres, and tarras mounted hye,
Came forth into the rout, and them t'array began.
Then foming tarre, their bridles they would champe,
(As wonts the Tartar by the Caspian lake,
Or that darke dreadfull hole of Tartare steepe,
Bred in the loathly lakes of Tartary,
Am now enforst a far vnfitter taske,
Dislikefull paine, so sad a taske to take,
So hard a taske, as life for hyre to sell;
That house-rome craues, yet would be loth t'assay
T'assayle with open force or hidden guile,
His foe t'assayle, or how himselfe to gard,
Hauing farre off espyde a Tassell gent,
And tassels gay. Wyde wonders ouer all
Resolued in one t'assemble all his force,
T'asswage his wrath, and pardon their mesprise.
Ne scarse good morsell all his life did tast,
Deserues to tast his follies fruit, repented payne.
Against the fourth Bulwarke, that is the Tast,
All passers by, to tast their lushious wine,
So she to Guyon offred it to tast;
Whose root and stalke so bitter yet did tast,
